</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="23" sentence-num-in-section="24" sentence-num-in-table="23" xml:id="C25.S1.p2.t1.s23">
primes
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="24" sentence-num-in-section="25" sentence-num-in-table="24" xml:id="C25.S1.p2.t1.s24">
on function symbols: derivatives with respect to argument.
</sentence>

</para>
   
<para xml:id="C25.S1.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="26" xml:id="C25.S1.p3.s1">
The main function treated in this chapter is the Riemann zeta function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p3.m1">\zeta\left(s\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="27" xml:id="C25.S1.p3.s2">
This notation was introduced in Riemann (1859).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C25.S1.p4">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="28" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.s1">
The main related functions are the Hurwitz zeta function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m1">\zeta\left(s,a\right)</Math> , the dilogarithm <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m2">\mathrm{Li}_{2}\left(z\right)</Math> , the polylogarithm <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m3">\mathrm{Li}_{s}\left(z\right)</Math> (also known as Jonquière’s function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m4">\phi\left(z,s\right)</Math> ), Lerch’s transcendent <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m5">\Phi\left(z,s,a\right)</Math> , and the Dirichlet <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m6">L</Math> -functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C25.S1.p4.m7">L\left(s,\chi\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
  
</section>
